<subSubSection id="C30EFBC0FF85FFC7B33A31A4FDD6FD42" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="281" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BABA84BFF85FFC7B33A31A4FDD6FD42" blockId="9.[826,1442,1422,1903]" lastBlockId="10.[144,759,198,648]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="281" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B33A31A4FC34FA6E" authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1888" box="[826,962,1422,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ceropalinae">Ceropalinae</taxonomicName>
was first erected by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF85FFC4B4B031A4FAB1FA6E" author="Haupt H" box="[1200,1351,1422,1444]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" pagination="109 - 197" refId="ref11269" refString="Haupt H. 1929. Weiterer ausbau meines Systems der Psammocharidae. Mit Beschreibung neuer gatungen und arten. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin 15: 109 - 197." type="journal article" year="1929">Haupt (1929)</bibRefCitation>
to comprise only two genera, 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B4583186FB3CFA0B" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1796" box="[1112,1226,1452,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ceropales" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9607459FF85FFC4B4583186FB3CFA0B" box="[1112,1226,1452,1473]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">Ceropales</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B50F3186FA6CFA0B" authorityName="Schulz. This" authorityYear="1906" box="[1295,1434,1452,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Irenangelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9607459FF85FFC4B50F3186FA6CFA0B" box="[1295,1434,1452,1473]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">Irenangelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF85FFC4B33A31E1FC2AFA2B" author="Townes H" box="[826,988,1483,1505]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" pagination="1 - 286" refId="ref12461" refString="Townes H. 1957. Neartic wasps of the subfamilies Pepsinae and Ceropalinae. United Sates National Museum Bulletin 209: 1 - 286." type="journal article" year="1957">Townes (1957)</bibRefCitation>
later included several genera that have been transferred since to 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B45E31C0FB32F9CA" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1845" box="[1118,1220,1514,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pepsinae">Pepsinae</taxonomicName>
and Notocyphinae. Our analyses are congruent with those of 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF85FFC4B4FD3222FA57F9D4" author="Shimizu A" box="[1277,1441,1544,1566]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" pagination="1 - 142" refId="ref12270" refString="Shimizu A. 1994. Phylogeny and classification of the family Pompilidae (Hymenoptera). Tokyo Metropolitan University Bulletin of Natural History 2: 1 - 142." type="journal article" year="1994">Shimizu (1994)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF85FFC4B371320DFBC9F9F7" author="Pitts JP &amp; Wasbauer MS &amp; von Dohlen CD" box="[881,1087,1575,1597]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" pagination="63 - 84" refId="ref11898" refString="Pitts JP, Wasbauer MS, von Dohlen CD. 2006. Preliminary morphological analysis of relationships between the spider wasp subfamilies (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae): revisiting an old problem. Zoologica Scripta 35: 63 - 84." type="journal article" year="2006">
Pitts 
<emphasis id="B9607459FF85FFC4B3B4320DFC13F9F6" box="[948,997,1575,1596]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
in recovering 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B4F1320DFA8AF9F7" authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1888" box="[1265,1404,1575,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ceropalinae">Ceropalinae</taxonomicName>
as monophyletic (clade F), and we confirm that 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B535326FFA57F990" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1796" box="[1333,1441,1605,1626]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ceropales" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9607459FF85FFC4B535326FFA57F990" box="[1333,1441,1605,1626]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">Ceropales</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B375324EFBF1F9B3" authorityName="Schulz. This" authorityYear="1906" box="[885,1031,1636,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Irenangelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9607459FF85FFC4B375324EFBF1F9B3" box="[885,1031,1636,1657]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">Irenangelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the sole representatives of 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B33A32A8FC3FF952" authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1888" box="[826,969,1666,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ceropalinae">Ceropalinae</taxonomicName>
. Although this lineage was poorly supported in the unconstrained analyses, support in the relaxed-clock analysis was high. The position of this group in the family, however, diverges from the results of previous authors. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF85FFC4B43232D7FB13F8D9" author="Shimizu A" box="[1074,1253,1789,1811]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" pagination="1 - 142" refId="ref12270" refString="Shimizu A. 1994. Phylogeny and classification of the family Pompilidae (Hymenoptera). Tokyo Metropolitan University Bulletin of Natural History 2: 1 - 142." type="journal article" year="1994">Shimizu (1994)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF85FFC4B52732D7FC76F8FB" author="Pitts JP &amp; Wasbauer MS &amp; von Dohlen CD" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" pagination="63 - 84" refId="ref11898" refString="Pitts JP, Wasbauer MS, von Dohlen CD. 2006. Preliminary morphological analysis of relationships between the spider wasp subfamilies (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae): revisiting an old problem. Zoologica Scripta 35: 63 - 84." type="journal article" year="2006">
Pitts 
<emphasis id="B9607459FF85FFC4B56932D4FA6CF8D8" box="[1385,1434,1789,1811]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
recovered 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B3FC3331FB72F8FB" authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1888" box="[1020,1156,1819,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ceropalinae">Ceropalinae</taxonomicName>
as the sister group to all other 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B37E3310FBF7F89A" box="[894,1025,1850,1872]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pompilidae</taxonomicName>
. In our study, 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF85FFC4B4A63310FAD9F89A" authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1888" box="[1190,1327,1850,1872]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ceropalinae">Ceropalinae</taxonomicName>
is strongly supported as the sister group to Notocyphinae. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF86FFC7B09034ECFECAFF16" author="Shimizu A" box="[144,316,198,220]" pageId="10" pageNumber="281" pagination="1 - 142" refId="ref12270" refString="Shimizu A. 1994. Phylogeny and classification of the family Pompilidae (Hymenoptera). Tokyo Metropolitan University Bulletin of Natural History 2: 1 - 142." type="journal article" year="1994">Shimizu (1994)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF85D5BAFF86FFC7B17634ECFDCEFF16" author="Pitts JP &amp; Wasbauer MS &amp; von Dohlen CD" box="[374,568,198,220]" pageId="10" pageNumber="281" pagination="63 - 84" refId="ref11898" refString="Pitts JP, Wasbauer MS, von Dohlen CD. 2006. Preliminary morphological analysis of relationships between the spider wasp subfamilies (Hymenoptera: Pompilidae): revisiting an old problem. Zoologica Scripta 35: 63 - 84." type="journal article" year="2006">
Pitts 
<emphasis id="B9607459FF86FFC7B1B434ECFE12FF11" box="[436,484,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="281">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
defined the subfamily by a set of non-unique homoplasies, including a reniform compound eye, the inner margin of eye converging below, and females with a straight stinger. However, 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF86FFC7B109356AFE6EFE9C" authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1888" box="[265,408,320,342]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ceropalinae">Ceropalinae</taxonomicName>
shares a large and exposed labrum and a compressed subgenital plate with its sister group, Notocyphinae. The exposed labrum is present in other spider-wasp genera (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF86FFC7B23435B6FF1BFE1B" authority="Gribodo" authorityName="Gribodo" authorityYear="1884" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Paracyphononyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9607459FF86FFC7B23435B6FD00FE7B" box="[564,758,412,433]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="281">Paracyphononyx</emphasis>
Gribodo
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF86FFC7B1313591FE8DFE1A" box="[305,379,443,464]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Pepsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9607459FF86FFC7B1313591FE8DFE1A" box="[305,379,443,464]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="281">Pepsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), but the extended labrum observed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C14D3C8FF86FFC7B11335F3FE5EFE25" authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1888" box="[275,424,473,495]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ceropalinae">Ceropalinae</taxonomicName>
and Notocyphinae distinguishes them from other genera by being large and almost as long as the clypeus, which gives the clypeus + labrum a diamond shape. Ceropalines are behaviourly distinguished by being kleptoparasites specialized on other pompilid species.
</paragraph>
